üìñ The Story of Beane

The Beane flows through the Upper Lea (Hertfordshire) catchment, where our eDNA survey sampled 11 sites along its length. Analysis of water samples revealed a rich invertebrate community with 10,407 distinct genetic sequences (ESVs) representing 1013 identified species and 337 families.

Compared to other chalk streams surveyed, the Beane shows one of the most biodiverse rivers in the study, ranking #1 of 10. The river supports 14 families of mayflies, stoneflies, and caddisflies (EPT) - key indicators of water quality.

Notable findings include the detection of conservation priority species (Water vole, Water shrew) and invasive species requiring management attention.
